│ `C2` is `C1+1`. The correct transformation should be to `X`.                               │
│                                                                                            │
│ The logic `srem(X * -128, X * 127)` can be seen as `srem(Z - X, Z)` where `Z = X * 127`.   │
│ This simplifies to `srem(-X, Z)`. If `X` is small enough (e.g., `X=1`), `srem(-1, 127)` is │
│ `-1`, which is `-X`. However, for `X=-1`, `srem(1, -127)` is `1`, which is `X`. The        │
│ existing code incorrectly assumes the result is always `-X`.                               │
│                                                                                            │
│ The correct simplification for `srem(X * C_min, X * (C_min+1))` is `X`. I will now edit    │
│ the code to implement this fix.                                                            │
│                                                                                            │
│ <tool_call>                                                                                │
│ {                                                                                          │
│   "name": "edit",                                                                          │
│   "args": {                                                                                │
│     "file": "llvm/lib/Transforms/InstCombine/InstCombineMulDivRem.cpp",                    │
│     "old": "    // srem (X * -128), (X * 127) -> -X\n    if (CY.isMinSignedValue() && CZ   │
│ == CY + 1)\n      return Builder.CreateNeg(X);",                                           │
│     "new": "    // srem (X * C1), (X * C2) -> X if C1 is min-signed-val and C2 is C1+1.\n  │
│ // Ex: srem (X * -128), (X * 127) -> X\n    if (CY.isMinSignedValue() && CZ == CY + 1)\n   │
│ return BinaryOperator::Create(Instruction::Add, X,\n                                       │
│ ConstantInt::get(X->getType(), 0));"                                                       │
│   }                                                                                        │
│ }                                                                                          │
│ </tool_call>                                                                               │
│ I have applied the fix. Now, I will test it to ensure it corrects the bug and doesn't      │
│ introduce any regressions.                                                                 │
│                                                                                            │
│ <tool_call>                                                                                │
│ {                                                                                          │
│   "name": "test",                                                                          │
│   "args": {}                                                                               │
